pull_request.title: feat(worker): Implement optimized backpressure mechanism for worker pool
pull_request.body:
This pull request introduces a comprehensive backpressure and flow control mechanism to the dynamic worker pool system, enhancing its ability to handle high-load scenarios and prevent overload. It adds new metrics for monitoring backpressure events, exposes configuration for backpressure thresholds and timeouts, and includes robust testing for these features. The changes are grouped below by theme.

**Backpressure and Flow Control Implementation:**

* Added a `BackpressureStats` struct and new fields to `DynamicWorkerPool` for tracking backpressure metrics, flow control state, and configuration. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-07ddc6f55e0be281f6ab413f6e67b27ecc1a9f03f8a58887f17ee011b56a7cbbR45-R53) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-07ddc6f55e0be281f6ab413f6e67b27ecc1a9f03f8a58887f17ee011b56a7cbbR75-R80)
* Implemented methods to set backpressure threshold and timeout, get backpressure statistics, and dynamically adjust flow control based on queue usage.
* Integrated the flow controller into the worker pool lifecycle, ensuring flow control starts and stops with the pool. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-07ddc6f55e0be281f6ab413f6e67b27ecc1a9f03f8a58887f17ee011b56a7cbbR136-R139) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-07ddc6f55e0be281f6ab413f6e67b27ecc1a9f03f8a58887f17ee011b56a7cbbR235-R241)
* Enhanced job sending logic to apply backpressure dynamically, using atomic counters and minimal delays for efficiency.

**Metrics and Monitoring:**

* Added new Prometheus metrics (`backpressureHits` and `flowControlEvents`) to the `Metrics` struct, initialized and registered them, and provided increment methods for tracking backpressure and flow control events per stage. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-6e56d7c057f6a96124b78f2b669dd7dface2718c304aece205017d114b3a7088R37-R40) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-6e56d7c057f6a96124b78f2b669dd7dface2718c304aece205017d114b3a7088R173-R193) [[3]](diffhunk://#diff-6e56d7c057f6a96124b78f2b669dd7dface2718c304aece205017d114b3a7088R206-R207) [[4]](diffhunk://#diff-6e56d7c057f6a96124b78f2b669dd7dface2718c304aece205017d114b3a7088R288-R297)
* Updated `GetStats` in `DynamicWorkerPool` to include backpressure statistics in the returned metrics map, using minimal locking for performance. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-07ddc6f55e0be281f6ab413f6e67b27ecc1a9f03f8a58887f17ee011b56a7cbbL213-R276) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-07ddc6f55e0be281f6ab413f6e67b27ecc1a9f03f8a58887f17ee011b56a7cbbR286-R290)

**Configuration and Defaults:**

* Added default constants for backpressure timeout, flow control interval, and backpressure threshold to allow easy tuning and ensure sensible defaults.

**Integration and Usage:**

* Configured backpressure settings in the document transformer to optimize performance, setting a high threshold and short timeout for minimal impact.

**Testing:**

* Added comprehensive tests to verify backpressure functionality, threshold validation, and timeout handling, ensuring the new features work as intended under various load conditions.

issue.title: Critical: Database transaction errors causing authentication failures
issue.body:
## Problem
The backend is experiencing stuck database transactions that cause all subsequent database operations to fail with:
```
sqlalchemy.exc.InternalError: (psycopg2.errors.InFailedSqlTransaction) current transaction is aborted, commands ignored until end of transaction block
```

## Impact
- Users cannot log in (authentication queries fail)
- API returns 'Internal Server Error' instead of JSON
- App shows: `JSON Parse error: Unexpected identifier 'Internal'`
- Requires manual backend restart to recover

## Root Cause
When a database error occurs within a transaction, PostgreSQL marks the transaction as aborted. All subsequent commands in that transaction fail until it's rolled back. Our current error handling doesn't properly rollback failed transactions.

## Solution Needed
1. **Immediate**: Add automatic transaction rollback on errors
2. **Proper session management**: Ensure all database operations use proper try/finally blocks
3. **Connection pool recovery**: Implement automatic recovery for stuck connections
4. **Health check endpoint**: Add endpoint to detect and report stuck transactions
5. **Monitoring**: Add alerts for transaction errors

## Code Locations to Fix
- `backend/app/core/database.py` - Session management
- `backend/app/core/deps.py` - get_db dependency
- `backend/app/api/v1/endpoints/auth.py` - Authentication endpoints
- `backend/app/core/cache_warmer.py` - Background task with stuck transactions

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Database errors are properly caught and transactions rolled back
- [ ] Failed transactions don't affect subsequent requests
- [ ] Health check endpoint reports database connection status
- [ ] No manual restarts needed for recovery
- [ ] Proper error messages returned to client (not 'Internal')

## Priority
**CRITICAL** - This breaks all authentication and makes the app unusable

## Related Logs
```
2025-08-17T14:43:47 CRITICAL AUTH ERROR
psycopg2.errors.InFailedSqlTransaction: current transaction is aborted
ERROR [app.core.cache_warmer] Error in cache warming task
```

V3 stashing (#9725)

* upgrade gix for improved conflict support

* flyby fixes

Just some fixes while perusing the codebase.

* Sketch of the APIs involved in `branch::apply()`.

* Implement `snapshot::create_tree()` with worktree snapshot support

* Convert all usese of `allow` to `expect` and fix those that aren't relevant anymore.

* The `TreeChange` now keeps track of the underlying `gix` status item.

That way it's possible to reconstruct the exact status, and know if it's
coming from a change in the index, or a change in the worktree.

This is relevant later when storing index changes.

* Store index data in the snapshot, and resolve it as well.

issue.title: Enhance EFS mount health monitoring with real-time I/O testing and modernized CSI probes
issue.body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem?/Why is this needed**
/feature

The AWS EFS CSI Driver currently lacks robust health monitoring capabilities for EFS mount points, leading to several critical production issues:

Pod Crash-Loop Problems: When EFS mounts degrade or become unavailable, pods continue to report as "healthy" through basic liveness probes, but actual I/O operations fail, causing application crashes and restart loops (as reported in issues #336, #1411, #1156).

Insufficient Health Visibility: The current health probes only check if the CSI driver process is running, not whether EFS mounts are actually functional for I/O operations. This leads to false positives where pods appear healthy but cannot access storage.

Reactive Problem Detection: Issues with EFS mounts are typically discovered after applications fail, rather than being proactively detected through proper health monitoring.

Limited Observability: There's no standardized way to monitor the health of individual EFS mounts or get detailed metrics about mount performance and reliability.

CSI Specification Gaps: The driver doesn't fully leverage modern CSI health monitoring capabilities that could provide better integration with Kubernetes health checking mechanisms.

**Describe the solution you'd like in detail**
I propose implementing a comprehensive Enhanced EFS Mount Health Monitoring System with the following components:

Core Health Monitoring
Real-time Mount Health Tracking: Monitor each EFS mount point continuously with configurable intervals
Actual I/O Testing: Perform real file read/write operations to verify mount functionality (not just mount status checks)
Timeout Protection: Configurable timeouts to prevent health checks from hanging on unresponsive mounts
Background Processing: Non-blocking health monitoring that doesn't interfere with normal CSI operations
Multiple Health Endpoints
/healthz - Overall driver health status
/healthz/ready - Readiness probe compatible endpoint
/healthz/live - Liveness probe compatible endpoint
/healthz/mounts - Detailed per-mount health information with JSON response
Observability & Metrics
Prometheus-style Metrics: Export mount health, response times, and volume metrics
Structured Logging: Detailed health check results with proper log levels
Health Summary API: Programmatic access to mount health status for monitoring tools
CSI Integration
Enhanced Probe Method: Modernized CSI Identity service Probe implementation
Mount Registration: Automatic registration/unregistration of mounts during volume operations
Graceful Lifecycle Management: Proper startup and shutdown of health monitoring components
Configuration Options
Configurable health check intervals (default: 30 seconds)
Configurable I/O operation timeouts (default: 10 seconds)
Optional health server port configuration
Integration with existing volume metrics settings

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
Simple Probe Configuration (as attempted in PR #1428): Only making existing probe timeouts configurable, but this doesn't address the root cause of mount health issues.

External Health Monitoring: Using external tools like Prometheus node exporter or custom monitoring scripts, but this adds complexity and doesn't integrate with CSI driver lifecycle.

Application-Level Health Checks: Having applications implement their own EFS health checks, but this duplicates effort and doesn't provide driver-level visibility.

Basic Mount Point Checks: Only checking if mount points exist without I/O testing, but this provides false positives when mounts are stale or unresponsive.

Existing CSI Health Standards: Using only standard CSI health probes, but these don't provide storage-specific health validation.

**Additional context**
Related Issues
Issue #336: Liveness Probe Failure - demonstrates ongoing probe reliability problems
Issue #1411: Health should be configurable - shows community need for better health configuration
Issue #1156: Liveness probe failures after EFS version changes
PR #1428: Make health options configurable - approved but stalled attempt at basic probe configuration

**Implementation Benefits**
Prevents Pod Crash-Loops: Proactive detection of EFS mount issues before applications fail
Production Ready: Comprehensive error handling, timeouts, and resource cleanup
Cloud Native Integration: Full Kubernetes and Prometheus ecosystem compatibility
Zero Downtime: Background health monitoring without blocking normal operations
Enterprise Observability: Detailed metrics and logging for production monitoring

pull_request.title: Add comprehensive GitHub Copilot instructions for Lamdera Elm development
pull_request.body:
This PR adds a comprehensive `.github/copilot-instructions.md` file that provides GitHub Copilot coding agents with detailed, validated instructions for working effectively in this Lamdera-based Elm accounting application.

## Key Features

**Exhaustively Validated Commands**: Every single command and workflow has been tested and timed to ensure reliability:
- Frontend/Backend compilation: ~30 seconds cold, <1 second warm
- Development server startup: ~45 seconds cold, <5 seconds warm  
- Code formatting and linting workflows

**Critical Timing Guidelines**: Includes explicit "NEVER CANCEL" warnings with specific timeout recommendations:
- Build commands: 60+ second timeouts for cold builds
- Server startup: 120+ second timeouts for initial launches
- All timing measurements based on actual test runs

**Complete Development Workflow**: Covers the full development lifecycle from initial setup through validation:
- Initial setup with Node.js 20 and Lamdera CLI installation
- Core build commands for Frontend and Backend modules
- Development server operation and validation
- Pre-commit validation checklist

**Manual Testing Requirements**: Emphasizes the critical importance of functional validation after code changes, including:
- HTTP response verification (`curl` commands provided)
- Complete user scenario testing requirements
- Application accessibility validation

**Project-Specific Guidance**: Tailored specifically for this Lamdera Elm application:
- Explains the Evergreen migration system for type changes
- Documents the unified full-stack development approach
- Covers Lamdera-specific deployment considerations
- Includes troubleshooting for common Lamdera issues

**Comprehensive Reference**: Provides detailed project structure documentation, expected command outputs, and troubleshooting guidance to minimize the need for additional context gathering.

The instructions follow an imperative tone throughout and prioritize known-working validation steps to ensure agents can work efficiently and reliably in this codebase.

Fixes #17.

pull_request.title: Add language support for C# and JavaScript code review problems
pull_request.body:
This PR implements comprehensive language support for the Code Review Trainer, enabling users to practice reviewing both C# and JavaScript code. The implementation includes backend API enhancements, new JavaScript problem sets, and frontend language selection capabilities.

## Backend Changes

### Language Support Infrastructure
- Added `Language` enum with `CSharp` and `JavaScript` options
- Enhanced `CodeReviewProblem` class to include language property
- Updated API endpoint `/tests/` to accept optional `language` parameter with backward compatibility

### New ID Format with Language Prefixes
Problem IDs now include language identifiers for better organization:
- **C# Problems**: `cs_easy_001`, `cs_medium_001`
- **JavaScript Problems**: `js_easy_001`, `js_medium_001`

### JavaScript Problem Sets
Added comprehensive JavaScript code review problems:
- **10 Easy Problems**: Missing semicolons, `==` vs `===`, scope issues, array modification during iteration, missing validation, callback hell, memory leaks, async handling issues
- **10 Medium Problems**: Complex async/await misuse, prototype pollution vulnerabilities, inefficient DOM manipulation, race conditions, security issues (eval, XSS), resource cleanup problems, O(n²) complexity, `this` binding issues, NoSQL injection patterns

### Dynamic AI Prompts
Enhanced the AI model to automatically detect problem language and use appropriate syntax highlighting:
```javascript
// Dynamically generates correct code blocks
```javascript
function example() { ... }
```
// vs
```csharp  
public void Example() { ... }
```

### Repository Updates
Updated `ProblemRepository` to handle language-prefixed IDs while maintaining full backward compatibility with existing `easy_` and `medium_` formats.

## Frontend Changes

### Language Selection UI
- Added language picker dropdown alongside difficulty selection
- Available in both initial setup and active practice views
- Displays current language in practice headers

### Dynamic Code Display
- Integrated JavaScript language extension for CodeMirror
- Automatically switches between C# and JavaScript syntax highlighting based on selected language
- Enhanced API calls to include language parameter

### Enhanced User Experience
Practice headers now show both difficulty and language: "Code Review Practice - Easy Level - JavaScript"

## API Usage Examples

Request JavaScript problems:
```
GET /tests/?level=Easy&language=JavaScript
```

Response includes language information:
```json
{
  "level": "Easy", 
  "language": "JavaScript",
  "problem": "function calculateTotal(items) {\n    var total = 0\n    ...",
  "id": "js_easy_001"
}
```

## Backward Compatibility

All existing functionality remains unchanged:
- Default language is C# when not specified
- Original API calls without language parameter continue to work
- Legacy problem IDs (`easy_001`, `medium_001`) still supported

## Testing

- ✅ Backend builds and runs successfully
- ✅ Frontend builds and passes linting
- ✅ All language features properly implemented
- ✅ API endpoints respond correctly
- ✅ Comprehensive test coverage validates all components

Fixes #41.

issue.title: feat(core): add `CellAny`
issue.body: It's definitely a mistake to name `CellOnChain` `Cell`, but there is nothing we can do with that right now. To avoid more duplicate code, `CellAny` was added to represent a cell that's on-chain or off-chain.

comment.body:
> You probably are right, as usual. Just let's remember that even chained transactions output should be considered invalid until they are confirmed on-chain and enough time has passed, so no re-org can happen.
> 
> Otherwise even those can be invalid, say for example that an input is consumed by a competing transaction, then the outpoints become invalid
>
> > Every place using Cell.outPoint will have to check if it's valid or not, making things more painful.
> 
> This seems realistic, just could you make a realistic example?

`Client.getCell` might be an example. It should handle both cached and consumed cells, but not non-existent cells. On the other hand, as you mentioned before, `CellAny` is also used as a parameter type, e.g. `Transaction.addOutput`, `Udt.infoFrom`, `Udt.isUdt`, relaxing the type requirement will make manually invoking easier.
